article.headline: Swoopes scores 21, Snow adds double-double
article.linkText: Swoopes sends surging Comets past reeling Storm
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Trailing by five points late in the game, the
Houston Comets called on forward Sheryl Swoopes. She delivered.

Swoopes finished with 21 points and nine assists, and the Comets
beat the Seattle Storm 71-67 Tuesday night for their third straight
victory.

The Comets (7-5) had a double-digit lead at Seattle on May 27
but faded and lost 79-69 in their first meeting this season.

Swoopes did not want that to happen again.

"This is a huge win for us because I think it really boosts our
confidence," she said. "I felt that we gave the game away when we
played up there, so I think to come back and win really says a lot
about the character of this team."

Michelle Snow added 11 points and 11 rebounds for her third
double-double of the season, and gave the Comets a 60-59 lead with
a layup with 4:58 remaining. They trailed by as many as five points
in the second half.

Betty Lennox got the Storm within 64-62 with a long 3-pointer
with 2:17 left. But Swoopes and Snow made seven of their eight free
throws down the stretch to seal the win.

"We were using this game to measure up to see where we are as a
team." Snow said. "We came out tonight and everyone was just
focused and ready to go. Swoopes did just about everything tonight
and really carried us when we needed her."

Seattle (7-7) has lost three straight and five of eight overall.
Houston had lost four in a row before beginning its winning streak.

Reserve Suzy Batkovik scored 16 points for the Storm, and Sue
Bird added 13 points and seven rebounds.

Forward Lauren Jackson did not play most of the second half,
finished with six points and took just four shots.

Visibly upset during postgame interviews, Jackson repeatedly
said she didn't know why she was taken out of the game.

"I honestly have no idea, why," she added.

Coach Anne Donovan declined to comment on Jackson's status.

Swoopes scored 14 points on 4-for-8 shooting to lead the Comets
to a 35-29 halftime advantage. She wound up five of six from the
line.

Jackson gave the Storm an early 10-7 lead, but the Comets
responded with a 9-3 run capped by a free throw from Atria
Phillips.
